I think a lot about millennials who were the last generation to be able to connect with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without having any reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundations for our lives.
That's why we're so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified private spaces.
unconsciously, we die to connect to the universal community that surrounded all of this
That's why so many of us watch shows like The Office or movies like Celebrity Presenter with obsessive devotion, full of short references, like memes.
we repeated these references, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't be sure if everyone has seen it.
there's too much to watch and no way to make sense of it all... will we escape hypersaturation?
we get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect with can be very flawed.
we enter parasocial relationships by paying more attention.
we understand that it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
lacking a collective awareness of the media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us stay critical.
some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall off.
we are in a turbulent period and I can't wait to find out where it will take us.
